{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:31:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:31:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18506"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18506"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.14,0.07,0.64,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80126"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11235"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6956"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26311"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80126"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver is the largest internal organ in the human body. It is divided into four lobes and has important relationships with surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical relationships of the liver?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The aorta runs inferior to the right lobe","The falciform ligament separates the right lobe from the quadrate lobe","The gallbladder fossa lies on the left lobe","The inferior vena cava runs posterior to the caudate lobe","The right hepatic vein divides the left lobe into segments"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior vena cava runs posterior to the caudate lobe\u003C/strong\u003E, which is bounded anteriorly by the porta hepatis and the fissure for the ligamentum venosum. The caudate lobe is the smallest of the four lobes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe aorta runs inferior to the right lobe\u003C/strong\u003E - The abdominal aorta runs inferior to the left lobe of the liver\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe falciform ligament separates the right lobe from the quadrate lobe\u003C/strong\u003E - The falciform ligament divides the liver into right and left lobes on its anterior surface\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe gallbladder fossa lies on the left lobe\u003C/strong\u003E - The gallbladder fossa is located on the visceral surface of the right lobe\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe right hepatic vein divides the left lobe into segments\u003C/strong\u003E - The left hepatic vein divides the left lobe into medial and lateral segments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver\u0027s four lobes are the right lobe (largest), left lobe, caudate lobe, and quadrate lobe. Each has specific anatomical relationships that are clinically relevant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The liver has four lobes: right, left, caudate, and quadrate.","The caudate lobe lies between the inferior vena cava posteriorly and the porta hepatis anteriorly.","The falciform ligament divides the liver into right and left lobes."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18506"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T15:14:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T15:17:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11235"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80126"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type